or individuals to overcome the inertia of entrenched national mentalities. Doing so depends on a particular nexus of policy expectations, national experience, and ready replacement ideas. In a sweeping comparative history, Legro explores the sources of strategy in the United States and Germany before and after the world wars, in Tokugawa Japan, and in the Soviet Union. He charts the likely future of American primacy and a rising China in the coming century.Rethinking the World tells us when and why we can expect changes in the way states think about the world, why some ideas win out over others, and why some leaders succeed while others fail in redirecting grand strategy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInternational organization. 0aInternational relations. 4aHistory. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170732240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501707322423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501707322/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles